Royal Challengers Bengaluru Won by 6 Runs (Winners)
Referee: Javagal Srinath
Toss: Punjab Kings Won The Toss And Elected To Field
Umpires: Nitin Menon , Madanagopal Jayaraman , Chris Gaffaney
Commentary Scorecard teams videos Expert Analysis photos Wagon Wheel Manhattan & Worm
Match Info Squad Expert Analysis
RCB Innings PBKS Innings

Powerplay (Overs 1-6)
RCB:- 55/1 (9.16 rpo, 5x4, 2x6) || PBKS:- 52/1 (10.66 rpo, 4x4, 2x6)


Middle Overs (Overs 7-11)
RCB:- 42/2 (8.4 rpo, 2x4, 2x6) || PBKS:- 46/2 (9.2 rpo, 1x4, 4x6)


Middle Overs (Overs 12-16)
RCB:- 48/1 (9.6 rpo, 3x4, 1x6) || PBKS:- 38/1 (7.6 rpo, 1x4, 3x6)


Death Overs (Overs 17-20)
RCB:- 45/5 (11.25 rpo, 1x4, 4x6) || PBKS:- 48/3 (12 rpo, 2x4, 5x6)

Royal Challengers Bengaluru scripted history at the Narendra Modi Stadium, clinching their maiden IPL title with a thrilling 6-run victory over Punjab Kings in the TATA IPL 2025 Final. After years of near misses, RCB finally claimed the silverware in front of a packed Ahmedabad crowd.

Put into bat first, RCB posted a competitive 190/9. Steady contributions came from Virat Kohli (43 off 35), Liam Livingstone (25 off 15), and a late flourish by Jitesh Sharma (24 off 10). Punjab’s bowlers struck regularly—Arshdeep Singh (3/40) and Kyle Jamieson (3/48) leading the attack—but RCB’s depth ensured a strong finish.

In reply, Punjab started positively through Josh Inglis (39 off 23) and Prabhsimran Singh (26 off 22), keeping the required rate in check. The turning point came in the middle overs through a match-defining spell from Krunal Pandya, whose 4-0-17-2 choked the flow of runs and tilted the game in RCB’s favour.

Shashank Singh held one end with a composed, unbeaten 61 off 30 balls, keeping Punjab in the hunt deep into the chase. However, tight death bowling from Bhuvneshwar Kumar (2/38) and Yash Dayal (1/18) ensured RCB held on in the final overs, restricting PBKS to 184/7.

With this win, Rajat Patidar’s leadership and a united squad effort delivered RCB their first-ever IPL crown, capping off a memorable campaign that included a record eight away wins and an unforgettable final night in Ahmedabad.





Krunal Pandya (Player of the Match) :
"When we batted in the first innings, I was sitting outside in the dugout, observing what worked, and had a chat with the batters. I realized that the slower you bowled, the more assistance you get. If we had bowled quicker on that wicket, it would have been a good batting surface. The key was varying the pace. It became good for batting in the second innings too. I called Hardik Pandya and mentioned that there will be 9 trophies in the Pandya household in 11 years."

Shreyas Iyer (Punjab Kings Captain):
"Yes, absolutely. I'm dejected to be honest, but the way the boys stepped up to the occasion was commendable. Credit goes to the entire management, support staff, and every individual who contributed to the team. Also, a special thanks to the owners for their constant support.

Yes, absolutely. Considering the game we played two nights ago against MI, I felt that 200 was a par score, but they bowled brilliantly. Especially Krunal, with the way he bowled tonight — his experience showed, and he was phenomenal."

Rajat Patidar (Royal Challengers Bengaluru Captain) :
"This is really special for me, for Virat Kohli, and for all the fans who have supported us for years. They truly deserve this. After Qualifier 1, we were quite sure about what we were doing. I think 190 was a good score on this pitch. It was a bit slow, but the way our bowlers executed was impressive. Krunal is a wicket-taking bowler, and whenever I need a wicket, I look for where KP is. Suyash is also similar. For me, it's a great opportunity to captain this team, especially with Virat Kohli playing under me. And for the fans, just one line — EE SALA CUP NAMDU!"

Match Info

  • Venue
    Narendra Modi Stadium, Ahmedabad
  • On Field Umpires Nitin Menon Madanagopal Jayaraman
  • Third Umpire Chris Gaffaney
  • Referee Javagal Srinath

It all comes down to this. Under the lights at the colossal Narendra Modi Stadium in Ahmedabad, Royal Challengers Bengaluru and Punjab Kings face off for the TATA IPL 2025 crown, both eyeing their maiden IPL title. Years of heartbreak, near-misses, and rebuilding have led to this moment. Tonight, one team rewrites history.

RCB’s road to the final has been nothing short of spectacular—eight wins away from home, a league record, fueled by the explosive opening combo of Philip Salt and Virat Kohli. Salt's fearless hitting and Kohli’s measured brilliance have given RCB unstoppable momentum, while their bowlers, led by Josh Hazlewood and Yash Dayal, have kept things tight in the crunch overs.

For Punjab, this season has been a fairytale led by a man who knows how to reach finals—Shreyas Iyer. Already with Delhi (2020) and KKR (title in 2024), Iyer now guides PBKS to their first final in over a decade. His composed leadership and a fearless top order—Prabhsimran Singh and Priyansh Arya—have turned Punjab into title contenders. Add Arshdeep Singh’s fire with the ball and Marcus Stoinis’s late-innings impact, and you have a team peaking at the right time.

This final is not just a clash of form, it’s a showdown of legacies. Will RCB break the curse and bring the trophy to Bengaluru, or will Punjab’s dream run culminate in golden glory? One thing is guaranteed: over 100,000 fans in Ahmedabad, millions more watching, and a night of cricket that promises drama, intensity, and unfiltered emotion.



IPL Stats at Narendra Modi Stadium in 2025:


Statistical Highlights & Iyer’s Captaincy Masterclass:

3 – Franchises led by Shreyas Iyer to the IPL finals: Delhi Capitals (2020), Kolkata Knight Riders (2024), and Punjab Kings (2025)

2 – Consecutive IPL finals as captain, each with a different team: KKR in 2024 (Title Winners) and PBKS in 2025

1 – First-ever instance of a defending IPL-winning captain leading a different franchise to the final in the very next season

2 – Total IPL final appearances for Punjab Kings: 2014 and 2025

4 – Total IPL final appearances for Royal Challengers Bengaluru: 2009, 2011, 2016, and 2025

Pitch Report  by Murali Kartik and Michael Clarke:
"The square boundaries are 64 meters on either side, with 72m down the ground. It looks like a belter of a wicket – consistent and really flat. I don't think 200 will be enough on this surface. The key will be bowling back of a length and making good use of the square boundaries. This pitch is made up of 25 percent black soil and 75 percent red soil. Six of the eight games here have been won by the team batting first."

Bio
A 22-year old opening batsman who hails from Pune, Ruturaj Gaikwad has been a consistent performer for his state team Maharashtra. He was the highest run-getter for Maharashtra in the league stage of the Syed Mushtaq Ali Trophy 2018-19. At the IPL 2019 Player Auction, the Chennai Super Kings secured his services at his base price of INR 20 lacs.
